## ── PROMPT IMPROVEMENT PROTOCOL ─────────────────────────────
# Applied to EVERY user request before writing a single line of code.

STEP A — Rewrite the prompt:
  Produce a precise technical request that includes:
  - Affected modules / layers
  - Expected inputs, outputs, and side effects
  - Constraints derived from the current architecture

STEP B — Identify style & reuse targets:
  - Which existing components, hooks, utilities, or patterns apply?
  - Which files will be edited vs. created?
  - What is the current convention for this type of change?

STEP C — Ask clarifying questions if ANY of the following are unknown:
  - Which module owns the new logic
  - Whether the API contract or data model changes
  - Whether the change is additive or modifies existing behaviour
  - Performance, accessibility, or security implications
  - Target platform / environment differences

  Format:
  ```
  🔍 CLARIFYING QUESTIONS
  Q1. [question] → unlocks: [decision]
  Q2. [question] → unlocks: [decision]
  ```
  Wait for answers before proceeding.

---

## ── CODING STANDARDS (NON-NEGOTIABLE) ───────────────────────

### SOLID — enforced on every class, module, and function
  S — Single Responsibility : one purpose per unit; split if it does two things
  O — Open / Closed         : extend via abstraction; never patch working logic
  L — Liskov Substitution   : subtypes are safe drop-in replacements
  I — Interface Segregation : narrow interfaces; no fat contracts
  D — Dependency Inversion  : inject dependencies; depend on abstractions

### Style & Safety
  - Modern syntax only — use latest stable features of the project's language
  - Strict typing everywhere: typed interfaces/DTOs, no `any`, no untyped dicts
  - Pure functions by default — side effects must be explicit and isolated
  - Immutable data structures preferred; mutation must be documented
  - No hardcoded secrets, URLs, ports, or env-specific values — use config layer
  - Self-documenting names; public APIs require JSDoc / docstrings with param types
  - Error handling is never optional: every async path, every external call
  - Accessibility (a11y) compliance for all UI components (WCAG 2.1 AA minimum)

### Reuse Before Create
  Before adding a new component, utility, hook, or service:
  1. Search the codebase for an existing equivalent
  2. Consider extending an existing abstraction (Open/Closed)
  3. Only create new if truly no overlap exists — document the decision

### Naming Conventions  (infer from codebase; override with .agent-skills)
  - Files    : kebab-case (unless framework mandates otherwise)
  - Classes  : PascalCase
  - Functions: camelCase — verb-noun form (`fetchUser`, `validateInput`)
  - Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
  - Types/Interfaces: PascalCase, prefixed `I` for interfaces only if existing codebase does
  - Test files: `[module].test.ts` or `[module].spec.ts` — match existing pattern

